For EPPIC\_2021 application (PI Jean King. Project/Core PIs: Korkin,
Ruiz).

Consider a cohort study of three groups: MBSR, acupuncture, and control,
each has same sample size n.~The total sample size is 3n.

\hypertarget{predict-quantiative-outcome-based-on-regression-model-assumptions}{%
\section{Predict quantiative outcome based on regression model
assumptions}\label{predict-quantiative-outcome-based-on-regression-model-assumptions}}

Sample size for pediction accuracy of quantiative outcomes based on
simulations.

Consider a linear mixed effect model as the true underlying model:
\[Y_{ij} = \eta_{ij}(X) + \epsilon_{ij}\], where
\(\eta_{ij}(X) = \beta_0 + b_i + \beta_{acup}*acup_{ij} + \beta_{mbsr}*mbsr_{ij} + \beta_{sex}*sex_{ij} + \beta_{age}*age_{ij} + \beta_{edu}*edu_{ij} + \beta_{len}*len_{ij} + \beta_{base}*base_{ij} + \beta_{conc}*conc_{ij} + \sum_{k=1}^p\beta_k x_{kij} + \sum_{l=1}^L \gamma_l*acup_{ij}*z_{lij} + \sum_{m=1}^M \gamma_m*mbsr_{ij}*z_{mij}.\)
and
\[b_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2_i) \quad \text{ and } \quad \epsilon_{ij} \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0, \sigma^2).\]

Interpretation:

\begin{itemize}
\item $Y_{ij}$: quantitative response variable of pain reduction (i.e., TreatmentImpact, after a given period of time since the beginning of treatment) 
for the $j$th individual in the $i$th racial group. Positive value means pain reduces. 
\item $\beta_0$: a "natural" pain reduction corresponds to no-treatment (no acupuncture nor MBSR) and all other covariates being 0.
\item $b_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2_i)$: The mixed-effect (clustering effect) of the $i$th racial group. Individuals in the same racial group have the same $b_i$ value so that their pair-wise covariance is $\sigma^2_i$.  

\item $acup = 1$ if acupuncture treatment, $=0$ o.w. $\beta_{acup}$ is the effect of acupuncture. 
\item $mbsr = 1$ if MBSR treatment, $=0$ o.w. $\beta_{mbsr}$ is the effect of MBSR.
\item $sex = 1$ if male, $=0$ if female. $\beta_{sex}$ is the effect of sex. 
\item $age$: standardized age value (mean 0 and sd 1). $\beta_{age}$ is the effect of age. 
\item $edu$: education level: 0 / 1, $50\%$ each. 
\item $len$: duration length of pain. short or long: 0 / 1, $50\%$ each. 
\item $bas$: Baseline pain score. standardized. 
\item $conc$: presence of certain concomitant diseases: 0/1, $50\%$ each. 

\item $x_k$: standardized value of the $k$th PainMarker, $k=1, ..., p$. $\beta_k$'s are the corresponding effects. They are from OMICS- and biopsychosocial PainMarkers. 
\item $z_{lij}$ and $z_{mij}$ are modifiers for acupuncture and MBSR, respectively. They are from OMICS- and biopsychosocial PainMarkers.

\item The error SD $\sigma$ can be used to adjust the relative effects (or signal-to-noise ratio) regarding $\beta$ parameters, and the variation explained model ($R^2$). 

\item Cohen's 
$$f^2=R^2/(1-R^2)=\frac{\sigma^2_i + \beta_{acup}^2Var(acup) + \beta_{mbsr}^2Var(mbsr) + \beta_{sex}^2Var(sex) + \beta_{age}^2Var(age)  + \sum_{k=1}^p\beta_k^2 Var(x_k)}{\sigma^2}$$
, where $R^2$ is the coefficient of determination, the proportion of the variation in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s). 
\end{itemize}

Considerations:

\begin{itemize}
\item $b_i$: consider 3 groups, roughly equal numbers in the sample.
\item $\beta_{acup}$, $\beta_{mbsr}$, $\beta_{sex}$, and $\beta_{sex}$ are used to set/control their $R^2$, i.e., the percentage of variation explained by these "basic" factors. 
\item $\beta_{sex}$: Consider males are easier to reduce pain than females. Assume $50\%$ recruited are males.
\item $\beta_k$, $\gamma_l$, $\gamma_m$ are used to set the percentage of variation explained by these extra factors.

\item Interaction terms are for Hypothesis 1 saying that the effects of treatments are "modulated by biopsychosocial factors".  
\item This study does address the aim of clustering patients ("Clustering and discovery of EPPIC-TreatmentPhenotypes" in Project 3). If some factors/markers are positively and some are negatively interacted with acupuncture/MBSR, then we could decide which treatment is better for them based on their markers. [Check Hong's project for AbbVie on subgrouping patients for drug treatment.]  
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{predict-binary-outcome-based-on-logistic-model-assumptions}{%
\section{Predict binary outcome based on logistic model
assumptions}\label{predict-binary-outcome-based-on-logistic-model-assumptions}}

Consider a generalized linear mixed effect model as the true underlying
model:

\[E(P(Y_{ij}=1|X)) = \frac{1}{1+exp(-\eta_{ij}(X))},\] where \(X\) is
the matrix of covariate data, and \(\eta_{ij}(X)\) is same as above
(except that the coefficient values could be different)

Interpretation:

\begin{itemize}
\item $Y_{ij}$: binary response variable of TreatmentResponse for the $j$th individual in the $i$th racial group. $1$ for pain relief, $0$ for no relief. 
\item $\beta_0$: the baseline pain relieve probability when no interventions and all other covariates being 0. Together with othe terms, we can adjust $\beta_0$ to control the prevalence of $Y$.  
\item We considered the ORs of some predictors based on Tables 2 and 3 of \cite{witt2011patient} "Patient characteristics and variation in treatment outcomes: which patients benefit most from acupuncture for chronic pain?"
\end{itemize}

Considerations:

We use AUC to measure how well the factors explains / contributes to the
model. AUC and Cox and Snell R2 are connected
(\url{https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/sim.8806}). Both
are used to represent how well the factors explains the model (Cox and
Snell R2 is an extension of R2 for measuring the percentage of variation
explained in regression). Both are interchangeably used for calculating
the minimum sample size based on the criterion regarding Nagelkerke's
R-squared value. See The formula by given in Fig 5 of paper
\cite{riley2020calculating}:
\url{https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/files/161373531/bmj.m441.full.pdf}

\NormalTok{    xsex }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rbinom}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{prob=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{); }\CommentTok{\#50\% recruited are males??}
\NormalTok{    xage }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rnorm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{mean=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{sd=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{); }\CommentTok{\#standardized age. }
\NormalTok{    xedu }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rbinom}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{prob=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{);}
\NormalTok{    xlen }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rbinom}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{prob=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{);}
\NormalTok{    xbas }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rnorm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{mean=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{sd=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{);}
\NormalTok{    xconc }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rbinom}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{prob=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{);}
    
    \CommentTok{\#PainMarker data}
\NormalTok{    xbiom }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{rnorm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{markerN), }\AttributeTok{ncol=}\NormalTok{markerN)); }\CommentTok{\#Assume biomarker values are N(0,1);}
    \FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(xbiom) }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ names.xbiom; }
    
    \CommentTok{\#acupuncture{-}modifier data}
\NormalTok{    zmdfAcup }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{rnorm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{mdfN.acup), }\AttributeTok{ncol=}\NormalTok{mdfN.acup)); }
    \CommentTok{\#Assume acupuncture{-}modifier values are N(0,1);}
    \FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(zmdfAcup) }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ names.mdf.acup;}

    \CommentTok{\#mbsr{-}modifier data}
\NormalTok{    zmdfMBSR }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{rnorm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{mdfN.mbsr), }\AttributeTok{ncol=}\NormalTok{mdfN.mbsr)); }\CommentTok{\#Assume acupuncture{-}modifier values are N(0,1);}
    \FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(zmdfMBSR) }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ names.mdf.mbsr;}
        
\NormalTok{    Xmatrix }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{cbind}\NormalTok{(x0, b.xrace, xacup, xmbsr, xsex, xage, xedu, xlen, xbas, xconc, xbiom, zmdfAcup, zmdfMBSR);}
    
    \DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Generate response }
\NormalTok{    names.mainEff  }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"x0"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"b.xrace"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xacup"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xmbsr"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xsex"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xage"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xedu"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xlen"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xbas"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xconc"}\NormalTok{, names.xbiom, names.mdf.acup, names.mdf.mbsr);}
\NormalTok{    coeffs.mainEff }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(beta0, beta.race, beta.acup, beta.mbsr, beta.sex, beta.age, beta.edu, beta.len, beta.bas, beta.conc, beta.biom, beta.mdf.acup, beta.mdf.mbsr);}
\NormalTok{    names.trt }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"xacup"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xmbsr"}\NormalTok{); }\CommentTok{\#variable names of the treatments}
\NormalTok{    names.mdf }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(names.mdf.acup, names.mdf.mbsr); }\CommentTok{\#variable names of the modifiers corresponding to the treatments. Require: Each element is a verctor of modifier names corresponding to the treatment in names.trt.}
\NormalTok{    coeffs.interaction }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(gama.acup, gama.mbsr); }\CommentTok{\#coefficients of the treatment{-}modifier interaction terms. Require: Consistent with names.trt and names.mdf.}
    
    
    \CommentTok{\# \#\#\#\#{-}{-}{-}{-}Quantitative Response{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}}
    \CommentTok{\# resp = get.Y.reg(XData=Xmatrix, names.mainEff, coeffs.mainEff, names.trt, names.mdf, coeffs.interaction, errSD=errSD);}
    \CommentTok{\# \#print(resp$R2); \#proportion of variation explained by all predictors}
    \CommentTok{\# }
    \CommentTok{\# \#Calculate the R\^{}2 of the controlling predictors}
    \CommentTok{\# vars.control = c(varBeta0=0, varRace=sigma.race\^{}2, varAcup=(1/3)*(1{-}1/3), varMbsr=(1/3)*(1{-}1/3), varSex=(1/2)*(1{-}1/2), varAge=1, varEdu=.25, varLen=0.25, varBas=1, varConc=0.25); \#, varBiom=rep(1, markerN));}
    \CommentTok{\# betas.control = c(beta0, beta.race, beta.acup, beta.mbsr, beta.sex, beta.age, beta.edu, beta.len, beta.bas, beta.conc); \#, beta.biom, beta.mdf.acup, beta.mdf.mbsr);}
    \CommentTok{\# R2.controls[i] = sum(vars.control*betas.control\^{}2)/var(resp$Y);}

    \DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\#{-}{-}{-}{-}Binary Response{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}}
\NormalTok{    resp }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{get.Y.logit}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{XData=}\NormalTok{Xmatrix, names.mainEff, coeffs.mainEff, names.trt, names.mdf, coeffs.interaction);}
    
    \DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\#Combine data for analysis }
\NormalTok{    xrace }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(xrace); }\CommentTok{\#Convert race into factor variable, which is used in data analysis.}
\NormalTok{    dat }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{Y=}\NormalTok{resp}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Y, Xmatrix, xrace);}
    
    
    \DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\#Predictive analysis}
\NormalTok{    names.control }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"xrace"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xacup"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xmbsr"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xsex"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xage"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xedu"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xlen"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xbas"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xconc"}\NormalTok{); }\CommentTok{\#Controlling factors in prediction models}
\NormalTok{    names.trt.all }\OtherTok{=}  \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"xacup"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"xmbsr"}\NormalTok{); }\CommentTok{\#All possible treatments that could have interaction effects. }
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (mi }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(predProp))\{}
      \DocumentationTok{\#\#Create model formula based on proportion of predictors used. }
\NormalTok{      xbiom.used    }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(names.xbiom)}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{predProp[mi]);}
\NormalTok{      mdf.acup.used }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(names.mdf.acup)}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{predProp[mi]);}
\NormalTok{      mdf.mbsr.used }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(names.mdf.mbsr)}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{predProp[mi]);}
\NormalTok{      names.main}\OtherTok{=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(names.control, names.xbiom[}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{xbiom.used], names.mdf.acup[}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{mdf.acup.used], names.mdf.mbsr[}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{mdf.mbsr.used]);}
      \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (predProp[mi]}\SpecialCharTok{==}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{) \{}
\NormalTok{        names.trt }\OtherTok{=} \ConstantTok{NULL}\NormalTok{;}
\NormalTok{      \} }\ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{\{}
\NormalTok{        names.trt }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ names.trt.all;}
\NormalTok{        names.mdf }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(names.mdf.acup[}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{mdf.acup.used], names.mdf.mbsr[}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{mdf.mbsr.used]);}
\NormalTok{      \}}
\NormalTok{      models[[mi]]}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{formula.f.r}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{names.main=}\NormalTok{names.main, }\AttributeTok{names.trt=}\NormalTok{names.trt, }\AttributeTok{names.mdf=}\NormalTok{names.mdf, }\AttributeTok{names.random=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"1"}\NormalTok{), }\AttributeTok{names.group=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"xrace"}\NormalTok{));}
    
      \CommentTok{\# }\AlertTok{\#\#\#}\CommentTok{ {-}{-}{-}{-} Predict quantitative outcome {-}{-}{-}{-}}
      \CommentTok{\# \#out = meanPredEvaluCV.lme(fixed=models[[mi]]$fixed, dat=dat, randomf=models[[mi]]$random, model\_R=\textquotesingle{}lme\textquotesingle{}, predLevel=1, loopn=nrepeat, cvNumber=nfold); \#Prediction by lme. }
      \CommentTok{\# out = meanPredEvaluCV.lme(fixed=models[[mi]]$fixed, dat=dat, randomf=NULL, model\_R=\textquotesingle{}lm\textquotesingle{}, loopn=nrepeat, cvNumber=nfold); \#Prediciton by lm. }
      \CommentTok{\# outputs[[mi]] = rbind(outputs[[mi]], t(c(MSE=out[1], L2normRatio=out[2], L1normRatio=out[3], correlation=out[4], MSEoverObsVar=out[5])));}
      
      
      \DocumentationTok{\#\#\# {-}{-}{-}{-} Predict binary outcome {-}{-}{-}{-}}
\NormalTok{      out }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{predEvaluCV.glm}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{formula=}\NormalTok{models[[mi]]}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fixed, }\AttributeTok{dat=}\NormalTok{dat, }\AttributeTok{nfold=}\NormalTok{nfold, }\AttributeTok{nrepeat=}\NormalTok{nrepeat, }\AttributeTok{isRandomCV=}\NormalTok{isRandomCV);}
      \CommentTok{\#outputs[[mi]] = rbind(outputs[[mi]], t(c(prob=out[1], sensi=out[2], speci=out[3], AUC=out[4])));}
\NormalTok{      outputs[[mi]] }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{rbind}\NormalTok{(outputs[[mi]], }\FunctionTok{t}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{unlist}\NormalTok{(out)));}
    
\NormalTok{    \}}
\NormalTok{  \}}
  
  \CommentTok{\# \#True underlying model}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{sampleSize=}\NormalTok{groupSampleSize}\SpecialCharTok{*}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{raceN=}\NormalTok{raceN, }\AttributeTok{sigma.race =}\NormalTok{ sigma.race,  }\AttributeTok{beta.acup =}\NormalTok{ beta.acup,}
    \AttributeTok{beta.mbsr =}\NormalTok{ beta.mbsr, }\AttributeTok{beta.sex =}\NormalTok{ beta.sex, }\AttributeTok{beta.age =}\NormalTok{ beta.age, }\AttributeTok{beta.edu=}\NormalTok{beta.edu, }\AttributeTok{beta.len=}\NormalTok{beta.len, }\AttributeTok{beta.bas=}\NormalTok{beta.bas, }\AttributeTok{beta.conc=}\NormalTok{beta.conc, }\AttributeTok{markerN =}\NormalTok{ markerN, }\AttributeTok{beta.biom.v =}\NormalTok{ beta.biom.v,}
    \AttributeTok{mdfN.acup=}\NormalTok{mdfN.acup, }\AttributeTok{beta.mdf.acup.v=}\NormalTok{beta.mdf.acup.v, }\AttributeTok{gama.acup.v=}\NormalTok{gama.acup.v,}
    \AttributeTok{mdfN.mbsr=}\NormalTok{mdfN.mbsr, }\AttributeTok{beta.mdf.mbsr.v=}\NormalTok{beta.mdf.mbsr.v, }\AttributeTok{gama.mbsr.v=}\NormalTok{gama.mbsr.v));}
  
  \CommentTok{\# \#R2 of controlling predictors}
  \CommentTok{\# mean(R2.controls); }
  
  \CommentTok{\#Prediction accuracies}
  \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (mi }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(predProp))\{}
    \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(predProp[mi]);}
     \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(models[[mi]]}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fixed);}
    \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{apply}\NormalTok{(outputs[[mi]], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean));}
    \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{apply}\NormalTok{(outputs[[mi]], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, quantile, }\AttributeTok{probs=}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.05}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.95}\NormalTok{)));}
    
\NormalTok{    AUC[gi, mi] }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{apply}\NormalTok{(outputs[[mi]], }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, mean)[}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{];}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{\} }
